      <h1 style="font-size:2.25rem;margin-top:1rem;margin-bottom:0.5rem">Reciprocating Saws for Metal: What Pro Trades Use for Pipe, Rebar, and Structural Steel</h1>
      <div style="color:#64748b;font-size:0.9rem">June 19, 2026 &middot; 10 min read</div>
    </div>

    <div class="prose">
      <p>A reciprocating saw that bogs down on schedule-40 steel pipe costs you billable hours and blade changes. When every minute on site counts, the difference between a saw that chews through rebar and one that stalls comes down to stroke length, orbital action, and the quality of the blade clamp. Metal cutting demands consistent blade speed under load, enough stroke to clear chips from the cut, and a clamp that holds the blade rigid at high reciprocation rates. This guide covers seven professional-grade saws that deliver on all three, from the Milwaukee M18 FUEL Sawzall to compact one-handed models for overhead conduit work.</p>

      <h2>What Makes a Recip Saw Effective on Metal</h2>
      <p>Metal is less forgiving than wood. A blade that deflects even 1/16-inch in a steel pipe will snap after a few cuts, wasting time and money. Three features separate a metal-cutting saw from a general-purpose one. First, stroke length: a 1-1/4-inch stroke clears swarf faster and extends blade life in metal. Longer stroke means the blade spends more time engaged in the cut per stroke, which improves cutting speed on thick-wall pipe and rebar. Second, orbital action: saws with orbital settings push the blade into the workpiece on the forward stroke and lift it on the return, improving chip clearance in metal. Not all reciprocating saws offer this, and it makes a measurable difference on steel. Third, blade clamp rigidity: a four-position clamp that locks the blade securely without lateral play prevents blade wandering and premature breakage on hard metals.</p>

      <h2>Best Overall: Milwaukee M18 FUEL Sawzall Gen II (2821-22)</h2>
      <p>The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B08WCDCTB1?tag=sciencesolved-20">Milwaukee 2821-22 M18 FUEL Sawzall Gen II</a> is the most powerful cordless reciprocating saw Milwaukee has built, and it shows in metal cutting tests. The POWERSTATE brushless motor delivers up to 2,900 strokes per minute with a 1-1/4-inch stroke length, the longest in the class. That stroke gives the blade enough travel to clear metal chips efficiently, reducing heat buildup that dulls blades prematurely. The ONE-KEY digital control lets you dial in speed and power settings per material: slow and steady for thin-gauge sheet metal, full speed for rebar and thick-wall pipe. The RedLink Plus intelligence system monitors motor temperature and adjusts power delivery to prevent overheating during sustained cuts in structural steel. The kit ships with two 5.0Ah batteries. For plumbers cutting cast iron, electricians trimming conduit, and ironworkers modifying rebar, this saw justifies its price in reduced blade changes and faster cuts. <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B08WCDCTB1?tag=sciencesolved-20">Check current price on Amazon</a>.</p>

      <h2>Best Compact: DEWALT DCS367B 20V MAX XR Compact Recip Saw</h2>
      <p>The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B01M69K91R?tag=sciencesolved-20">DEWALT DCS367B 20V MAX XR Compact Reciprocating Saw</a> proves that compact form factor does not have to mean compromised metal-cutting performance. It delivers 0-3,200 SPM with a brushless motor and a pivoting adjustable shoe that gives you precise angle control on metal surfaces. At 6.3 pounds, it is light enough to use one-handed for overhead conduit cutting, but the key advantage for metal work is the variable-speed trigger, which gives you the control needed for starting cuts on curved pipe without blade walking. The keyless lever-action blade clamp accepts standard 1/2-inch shank blades and releases with one gloved hand. With 4,500-plus ratings at 4.7 stars, this is the most-reviewed compact recip saw on the market, and for good reason: it cuts cleanly through EMT conduit, copper pipe, and steel studs without the bulk of a full-size saw. <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B01M69K91R?tag=sciencesolved-20">Check current price on Amazon</a>.</p>

      <h2>Best Stroke Length: Makita XRJ05Z 18V LXT Brushless Recip Saw</h2>
      <p>The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B01IU92IYI?tag=sciencesolved-20">Makita XRJ05Z 18V LXT Brushless Reciprocating Saw</a> delivers 0-3,200 SPM with a 1-1/4-inch stroke, matching the Milwaukee Sawzall for stroke length in a lighter package at 7.4 pounds with battery. The crankless reciprocating mechanism reduces vibration significantly compared to traditional gear-driven saws, which matters when you are making multiple cuts in rebar or angle iron over the course of a day. Less vibration means less operator fatigue and more consistent cuts. The variable speed trigger with lock-on lets you maintain a steady cutting pace through long sections of pipe without holding the trigger down. The XPT (Extreme Protection Technology) seals the motor and electronics against dust and moisture, which is relevant on demolition sites where metal cutting often happens alongside concrete dust and water. For framers cutting steel studs and plumbers modifying cast iron, the Makita's stroke-to-weight ratio is hard to beat. <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B01IU92IYI?tag=sciencesolved-20">Check current price on Amazon</a>.</p>

      <h2>Best All-Round Cordless: Milwaukee 2720-20 M18 FUEL Sawzall</h2>
      <p>The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B081P4XF25?tag=sciencesolved-20">Milwaukee 2720-20 M18 FUEL Sawzall</a> is the first-generation M18 FUEL Sawzall and remains a strong choice for metal cutting at a lower entry price than the Gen II. It delivers 0-2,800 SPM with a 1-1/8-inch stroke, still longer than most compact saws. The gear-protected clutch coupling protects the drivetrain from sudden blade lockups, which happens frequently when a metal-cutting blade catches the edge of a cut in rebar or hits a hidden weld. The universal blade clamp accepts all standard 1/2-inch shank blades without adapters. With over 3,500 ratings at 4.7 stars, this saw has proven itself across thousands of job sites. The main trade-off versus the Gen II is the lack of orbital action and ONE-KEY digital controls, but for contractors who need a reliable metal-cutting saw without the premium features, this model delivers on the fundamentals. <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B081P4XF25?tag=sciencesolved-20">Check current price on Amazon</a>.</p>

      <h2>Best Value: DEWALT DCS380B 20V MAX Recip Saw</h2>
      <p>The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B007NVSTCK?tag=sciencesolved-20">DEWALT DCS380B 20V MAX Reciprocating Saw</a> is the most popular cordless recip saw on Amazon by volume, with over 8,000 ratings at 4.6 stars. It hits 0-3,000 SPM with a 1-1/8-inch stroke and features a variable speed trigger that gives you fine control for starting cuts on metal surfaces without blade bounce. The four-position blade clamp lets you orient the blade for flush cuts against pipe hangers, junction boxes, and structural supports. The adjustable pivoting shoe extends blade life by letting you use different sections of the blade across multiple cuts. It lacks the brushless motor of the DEWALT DCS367B, which means shorter runtime per battery charge, but for contractors who already have 20V MAX batteries and need a metal-cutting saw for regular work, the DCS380B delivers reliable performance at a price that leaves room in the tool budget for a quality set of metal-cutting blades. <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B007NVSTCK?tag=sciencesolved-20">Check current price on Amazon</a>.</p>

      <h2>Best One-Handed: DEWALT DCS369B ATOMIC 20V MAX Compact</h2>
      <p>The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B082BTT92H?tag=sciencesolved-20">DEWALT ATOMIC 20V MAX Reciprocating Saw (DCS369B)</a> is purpose-built for tight-space metal cutting that full-size saws cannot reach. The compact one-handed design fits between ceiling joists, inside equipment panels, and behind wall cavities where electricians and HVAC contractors frequently cut conduit and EMT. It delivers 0-3,200 SPM with a brushless motor and keyless blade clamp. At 4.5 pounds, it is the lightest saw in this guide, which makes a difference when you are holding it overhead to cut conduit runs. With over 2,500 ratings at 4.6 stars, it has strong adoption among electricians and low-voltage contractors. The trade-off is a shorter stroke and less torque than full-size models, so it is best suited for thin-wall conduit, copper pipe, and light rebar rather than structural steel or thick-wall cast iron. <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B082BTT92H?tag=sciencesolved-20">Check current price on Amazon</a>.</p>

      <h2>Best Compact Alternative: Makita XRJ08Z 18V LXT Compact Brushless</h2>
      <p>The <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0BMWBJJ4J?tag=sciencesolved-20">Makita XRJ08Z 18V LXT Compact Brushless Recip Saw</a> is Makita's answer to the one-handed compact category, with a 0-3,500 SPM brushless motor that reaches the highest reciprocation rate of any saw in this guide. At 4.9 pounds with battery, it splits the difference between a one-handed compact and a full-size saw. The tool-less blade change mechanism is fast and reliable, and the built-in LED light illuminates the cut area in dark spaces like crawlspaces and equipment rooms where electricians and plumbers commonly cut metal pipe. The compact design means a shorter stroke than the full-size Makita XRJ05Z, so it is best for thin-wall conduit, cable trays, and light metal framing rather than heavy structural work. For contractors who need a second saw specifically for tight-space metal cuts, this is a capable companion to a full-size model. <a href="https://www.amazon.com/dp/B0BMWBJJ4J?tag=sciencesolved-20">Check current price on Amazon</a>.</p>

      <h2>Metal-Cutting Blades: The Real Performance Differentiator</h2>
      <p>The saw is only half the equation. A good reciprocating saw with a cheap blade will cut slower and generate more heat than an average saw with a premium metal-cutting blade. For steel and cast iron, use bi-metal blades with 14-24 teeth per inch. For thin-gauge sheet metal and aluminum, use 10-14 TPI blades. For rebar and structural steel, 6-10 TPI aggressive blades with thicker gauge material resist breakage when the blade hits a hard edge. Brands like Lenox, Bosch, and Milwaukee produce purpose-specific metal-cutting blades in multi-packs that cover the full range of metal thicknesses you will encounter on a construction site. Budget for blades as an ongoing consumable. On heavy metal cutting days, plan for one blade change per 20-30 cuts in schedule-40 steel pipe, fewer in rebar and structural steel.</p>

