      <h2>Conclusion</h2>
      <p>Metal cutting demands specific saw features that a general-purpose demolition saw may not provide. If you cut rebar, structural steel, or thick-wall pipe daily, the Milwaukee M18 FUEL Sawzall Gen II with its 1-1/4-inch stroke and orbital action delivers the fastest cuts and longest blade life. If you need a compact saw for overhead conduit work and tight-space metal cutting, the DEWALT DCS367B XR gives you pro-grade power in a manageable package. And for contractors who want the best stroke-to-weight ratio for steel studs and general metal work, the Makita XRJ05Z pairs industry-leading run time with reduced vibration that keeps you cutting longer. Whatever saw you choose, invest in quality metal-cutting blades matched to the gauge and type of metal you work with most. The saw does the work, but the blade does the cutting.</p>

